# A GeoAI-Based Framework for Geospatial Flood Risk Mapping and Urban Waterlogging Prediction

**Authors:** [Author Name(s)]
**Affiliation:** [Institution], Ernakulam, Kerala, India
**Email:** [contact@institution.edu]

---

## Abstract

Urban waterlogging resulting from extreme precipitation events is a critical infrastructure and public safety challenge in low-lying coastal districts. Ernakulam district, Kerala, India, is acutely vulnerable to flooding as demonstrated by the catastrophic 2018 Kerala flood, during which large urban areas experienced severe inundation. Traditional GIS-based flood delineation methods fail to capture the spatially complex interactions between terrain morphology, land surface cover, and drainage capacity in heterogeneous urban landscapes. This paper presents a GeoAI-based framework that integrates Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) spatial learning with multi-source geospatial raster data for pixel-wise flood susceptibility prediction. The system ingests a seven-channel input stack comprising digital elevation, terrain slope, log-scaled flow accumulation, distance to extracted drainage channels, drainage density, built-up area density, and a user-controlled rainfall intensity scalar. Drainage channels are extracted from the NASA Digital Elevation Model–derived flow accumulation raster using percentile-based thresholding; proximity and density metrics derived from these channels serve as scientifically valid surrogates for unavailable official drainage network data. The Sentinel-1 SAR-derived binary flood extent mask of the 2018 Kerala flood event is used as ground truth for supervised training of the U-Net CNN. Rainfall is not predicted; rather, it is injected at inference time as a scalar scenario input, enabling dynamic what-if spatial risk simulation. The resulting system provides flood probability maps, risk class overlays (Safe, Moderate, High, Critical), and an interactive Leaflet-based web dashboard with a rainfall slider, place search, and configurable alert logic, serving both disaster management operators and urban planners.

---

## I. Introduction

Flood disasters are among the most economically destructive and life-threatening natural hazards globally, with urban flooding in particular continuing to intensify due to rapid imperviousness growth, inadequate drainage infrastructure, and the increasing frequency of extreme precipitation events driven by climate variability [1]. Coastal districts of Kerala, India, record among the highest flood frequency in the subcontinent due to the combined effect of monsoon intensification, relatively flat estuarine terrain, and high urban density [2]. The 2018 Kerala floods—classified as the worst in a century—inundated over 20,000 km² and displaced approximately 1.5 million people, with Ernakulam district being one of the most severely affected [3].

Conventional methods for flood risk assessment rely on hydrodynamic models (e.g., HEC-RAS, SWMM) that require dense ground-based observations, calibrated drainage network GIS layers, and considerable computational infrastructure [4]. Statistical GIS approaches, such as logistic regression or analytical hierarchy process (AHP) overlays, perform multi-criteria evaluation of terrain and land use but do not capture nonlinear spatial interactions and scale poorly with resolution [5]. Remote sensing–based flood inundation mapping using SAR imagery provides post-event extent mapping but cannot autonomously generate predictive spatial risk outputs for novel rainfall scenarios [6].

Deep learning, and CNNs in particular, have demonstrated exceptional capability in capturing spatially local feature interactions across multi-band raster imagery with translational invariance—qualities directly applicable to pixel-wise geographic risk classification problems [7]. CNN-based geospatial models, trained on patch-extracted feature stacks derived from aligned raster layers, can encode terrain–landcover–hydrology interactions at high spatial fidelity without requiring access to physically calibrated drainage network models.

This paper proposes and implements a GeoAI framework—combining GIS-derived geospatial raster engineering with a U-Net CNN—capable of producing flood susceptibility maps across Ernakulam district at native raster resolution. A key innovation is the treatment of rainfall intensity as a user-configurable scenario scalar injected dynamically at inference time, enabling spatial simulation of flood risk under arbitrary precipitation conditions without time-series modeling. The system is delivered as a production-ready web dashboard integrating FastAPI, Leaflet.js, and raster tile serving.

---

## II. Related Work

### A. GIS-Based Flood Susceptibility Mapping

Early approaches to flood susceptibility mapping employed GIS overlay and multi-criteria decision analysis (MCDA), computing weighted sums of factors such as elevation, slope, drainage density, and land use/land cover (LULC) [8]. Tehrany et al. applied bivariate statistical methods and logistic regression over GIS-derived rasters in the Kelantan River basin, achieving moderate predictive accuracy but limited generalization [9]. These approaches require expert-defined factor weights, are sensitive to subjective thresholds, and do not learn spatial patterns from data.

### B. Machine Learning for Flood Risk

Shallow machine learning models—including Support Vector Machine (SVM), Random Forest (RF), and Maximum Entropy (MaxEnt)—have been extensively applied to flood susceptibility mapping, often outperforming MCDA approaches [10]. Khosravi et al. demonstrated that ensemble methods such as RF achieve AUC values above 0.87 in validation sets derived from catalogued flood inventory points [11]. However, these pixel-wise models treat each sample independently and do not exploit spatially contextual neighbourhood structure, limiting their ability to represent connected terrain features such as valley networks and drainage pathways.

### C. Deep Learning Approaches

Convolutional Neural Networks overcome the neighbour-blindness of classical ML by learning spatially local feature maps through convolution kernels. Luo et al. applied FCN-based pixel-wise classification to SAR flood extent delineation [12]. Kabir et al. trained a U-Net on multi-source remote sensing features for urban flood damage mapping [13]. The fully convolutional U-Net architecture, originally developed for biomedical image segmentation, is particularly suited to dense prediction problems in remote sensing due to its skip connections that preserve fine spatial detail [14]. However, few studies integrate explicit drainage proximity metrics derived from DEM flow routing as model inputs, and fewer still implement scenario-based dynamic rainfall injection at inference time.

### D. SAR for Flood Mapping

Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) imagery from Sentinel-1 provides cloud-independent, dual-polarisation backscatter data sensitive to surface water extent changes due to the specular reflection characteristics of standing water [15]. The 2018 Kerala flood event has been extensively studied using Sentinel-1 C-band imagery; binary flood masks derived through automated change detection (baseline vs. flood imagery threshold comparison) are available for the event period and constitute a reliable ground truth dataset [16].

### E. Research Gap

This work addresses the following identified gaps: (i) the absence of drainage network–aware deep learning flood models when official drainage GIS is unavailable; (ii) the lack of rainfall scenario injection capability in spatial CNN flood models; and (iii) the absence of end-to-end deployable GeoAI dashboards for operational flood risk communication integrating real-time rainfall scenario simulation.

